Depending on how religious or spiritual you are, there's another important dimension to the argument - most people believe in some sort of afterlife... and a lot of those people, including Christians, believe that animals don't go to one.  They are taught that animals live in the here and now, but just like they do not possess the capacity to reason (I consider this a given, but I remember a discussion about this a few months ago too)... they also do not possess any sort of immortal soul (also debatable, but bear with me for the sake of the argument... some people believe it).  Therefore, is not saving the life of the animal doing it a favor in a big way, since killing it consigns it to non-existence forever?  On the other hand, if the animal *does* have a soul, would it not be doing it a favor to consign it to a better life?  Do we have that right to judge an animal so, as we presumably do not a human (doctor-assisted &quot;suicide&quot; of a comatose patient would be considered murder)?  Wouldn't the fact that animals do fight for life so hard irregardless of circumstance indicate that they do not have souls?  Or maybe its just the fact that they operate solely on instinct, so they obviously dont think about an afterlife...<br>
